latestIgtvVideos.title: Lock the shoulders before lifting objects from the ground to avoid injuries
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Whenever I enter the gym, l see nearly everyone lifting with a bad posture. Various injuries like ROTATORS CUFF, ACL, ANKLE SPRAINS, WRIST SPRAINS and LOWER BACK INJURIES, happen because of regular lifting in an improper form.

Here I have shown a hack of how you can lock your shoulders and lift. This will increase muscle activation, strength and furthermore save you from injuries.

This can be used in majority of the exercises you do.
Chest presses, shoulder presses, bicep curls and many more.

Don't ignore form, cause if you do it might happen that gradually with time or suddenly, but eventually you will get injured.

#exercise #workout #gym #fit #fitness #lift #weightlift #hack #fitnessconsultant #fitnessfreal #influencer #motivation #health #life #locktheshoulders.

latestIgtvVideos.title: How to do an agility drill.
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
(watch Ig tv for the proper video)
Things to be kept in mind while doing these drills.
1. Make sure you are using proper shoes for the proper terrain.
2. Take short quick strides while turning or changing directions. keep your back straight and center of gravity low. (bend)
3. Land on your toes while turning or changing directions. (don't land on heels)
4. Use videos to keep a track on your technique and progress.

Sweet potatoes are a complex carbohydrate, providing slow-releasing energy, which helps:

	•	Improve workout performance
	•	Enhance recovery
	•	Support insulin response post-workout (important for nutrient uptake)

	•	Vitamin A (beta-carotene): Antioxidant that supports immune function and reduces inflammation.

	•	Vitamin C: Aids collagen production and tissue repair.
	•	Manganese & Copper: Essential for enzyme function in energy metabolism.

	•	Potassium: Helps regulate fluid balance and prevents cramping during training.

•	Useful in both bulking and lean mass phases, depending on portion size.

•	Supports gut health, which is increasingly linked to nutrient absorption and systemic inflammation—both of which affect muscle recovery and growth.
